\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\keepn\fi0\sb360\sa200\li0\ri0\f1\fs48\b1\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Polymetric Notation\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Explicit polymetric notation is the use of different time signatures in effect simultaneously.  Although this device is not common, composers have used explicit polymetric notation for hundreds of years with varying interpretations. There are two main interpretations of polymetric notation, distinguished by whether the intention is\par
\pard\tx663\tx936\tx6600\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 	I.	to notate unequal note values without using tuplet notation, or\par
\pard\tx663\tx936\tx6600\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 	II.	to specify cross rhythms using equal note values.\par
\pard\tx663\tx4400\tx6600\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 It is important to be able to distinguish which interpretation is being adopted in a musical design, as it turns out that the computational implications of the two interpretations are quite different.  All known uses of explicit polymeter may be explained by one or other of these interpretations.  In a few exceptional cases it turns out that different time signatures are being used to notate a piece which is in fact not polymetric or\i0  that uniform time signatures could be used without loss of generality.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i1\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i1\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0\b Interpretation I.\b0 \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 The first interpretation is illustrated by the following extract from Variation V. of Johannes Brahms: \i Variazioni\i0 , Op. 35 of 1866 (in all the musical examples that follow, only timing and pitch information is shown; articulation and phrasing marks are suppressed):\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_8.eps \width8840\height2080
}¨} \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Here the intention is to notate a 4-against-6 rhythm, but without using triplet notation for the notes in the lower staff.  Instead, opposing time signatures of \b 2\b0 /\b 4\b0  and \b 6\b0 /\b 8\b0  are used with coinciding barlines. We say that a system has \i coinciding barlines\i0  when the barlines at the same beatline are aligned in the same vertical axis.  The coincidence of barlines together with the spacing of the notes suggests that note values in the upper staff are in a nonunity proportion to the note values on the lower staff.  The constant of proportionality \i x\i0  is easily determined from the time signatures by the equation (2/4)\i x\i0  = (6/8),  or \i x\i0  = 1.5.  Thus, a quaver on the upper staff has a duration 1.5 times the duration on the lower staff.  This proportional relation is properly termed \i sesquialtera\i0\i0 , and it is clear that Interpretation I. pertains.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0\i0 In Calliope this scheme is notated by entering the music as above, ensuring that the \b 6\b0 /\b 8\b0  signature has a proportionality ratio set (in the Inspector) to 2/3, as shown here:\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qc\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0\i0 {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_1.tiff \width3840\height4260
}¨} \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 A mathematically equivalent alternative would be to set the proportionality ratio of the \b 2\b0 /\b 4\b0  time signature to 1.5/1, but in this example, it is better `compress' the spacing of the lower staff than to expand spacing of the upper staff.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 The remaining point to notice is that barlines are coincident.  This is specified in the Adjustment Options aspect of the System Inspector, as shown here:\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qc\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_9.tiff \width3980\height2100
}¨} \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Because the proportionality ratio applies only to the notes and rests governed by a given time signature, it is important that the time signatures at the beginning of each system have the proportionality ratios set appropriately.  The same is true of the adjustment option, which should be set appropriately for each system.  In practice, this is not a difficulty because these attributes will be copied over when new systems are created from previous ones.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 The first interpretation applies also to this extract (bars 56-60) from Paul Hindemith:  \i Konzert \i0\i0 for trumpet and bassoon with strings (1949): \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_7.eps \width8840\height5880
}¨} \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0\i\i0 H\i0 ere the \i\i sesquialtera\i0\i0  relation is retained over several changes of time signature, but a triplet is also used when the intention is for the rhythms to break the pattern and coincide.  Again because the interpretation is clearly notated by time signatures, coinciding bars and explicit triplet notation, this does not present computational problems provided that Interpretation I is assumed.  The note values of the instrumental parts are always two-thirds the duration of the note values in the grand staff, regardless of the change of signature, except where unequal notation is used.  To notate, change the proportionality ratios of the \b 3\b0 /\b 2\b0  and \b 2\b0 /\b 2\b0  time signatures to 3/2.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0\i0 Interpretation I. is of course, not restricted to \i\i sesquialtera\i0\i0  proportions, as is illustrated by this extract from Gabriel Piern›:  violin sonata Op. 36:\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qc\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_6.eps \width6640\height1700
