\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b1\i1\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Interpretation II.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 An example of the second interpretation is taken from Hindemith: \i Mathis der Maler\i0  (1937): {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_5.eps \width9020\height1780
}¨} Although different time signatures are used, it is clear from the positioning of barlines and events that note values are equal thoughout the system (that is, a minim on the first staff is of the same duration as a minim on the grand staff).  The interpretation is different from that discussed previously, because any constant of proportionality that may be derived from the time signatures cannot be used to calculate the relative durations of musical events.  Here the durations of note values agree in all staves, but because the time signatures specify different numbers of beats per measure, barlines do not coincide until six beats have elapsed (6 is the least common multiple of 2 and 3, the numerators of the time signatures).  Here the intention appears simply to control the timing of primary stresses.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Therefore, to notate this, the proportionality ratios of all time signatures remain at the default 1/1, but each system should specify non-coinciding barlines, as shown in the previous example.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 One of the most frequently cited examples of polymetric notation happens to be one in which Interpretations I and II are both identifiable in the same passage. The following is an extract from the finale to Act I of W.A. Mozart: \i Don Giovanni\i0 :\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_2.eps \width8840\height5800
}¨} \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 The events governed by the \b 2\b0 /\b 4\b0  and \b 3\b0 /\b 4\b0  signatures are to be read in Interpretation II (equal note values, with differing beats per bar), while the events governed by the \b 3\b0 /\b 8\b0  are to be read in interpretation I (unequal note values) in order to implement an alternative to notating triplets in \b 3\b0 /\b 4\b0 .\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 To notate this,\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 1. Set the proportionality ratios of the two \b 3/8\b0  signatures to 2/3.\par
